snippet.textDisplay:
One reason Gollum works is digital color grading. They weren't able to do subsurface light refraction or surface light diffusion with his flesh, but, thanks to heavyhanded grading of the movie, none of the surfaces in LOTR look naturally lit, so Gollum doesn't stand out.
Also, I'm surprised these guys don't know that they did Monster Bilbo by morphing to a puppet.
snippet.textOriginal:
One reason Gollum works is digital color grading. They weren't able to do subsurface light refraction or surface light diffusion with his flesh, but, thanks to heavyhanded grading of the movie, none of the surfaces in LOTR look naturally lit, so Gollum doesn't stand out.
Also, I'm surprised these guys don't know that they did Monster Bilbo by morphing to a puppet.

snippet.textDisplay: About the not being able to do CG in the year 2000, is that really true?  They could have. Was it really a technical limitation? NO. You guys are kind of misleading people to believe that they didn't include CGI in the lord of the rings just because of technical reasons, because they couldn't do it at the time. Is that really true though? They had the technology. The better answer would be that the technology was there, but they were on a strict schedule to release a film and time was more of a factor than quality at the time of release.
